e denote the features as $ oldsymbol x_0, \dotsc,  oldsymbol x_n$ and collect them into a vector $ oldsymbol {x}$, and the price of the houses as $y$. Assuming that we havea prediction model in the way such that $\hat{y}_i = f( oldsymbol {x}_i) =  oldsymbol 	heta^T oldsymbol {x}_{i}$. If we collect the dataset into a $(N,D)$ data matrix $ oldsymbol X$, we can write down our model like this:  egin{bmatrix}  oldsymbol{x}_1^T \ \vdots \  oldsymbol{x}_N^T \end{bmatrix}  oldsymbol{	heta} =  egin{bmatrix} y_{1} \ \vdots \ y_{2} \end{bmatrix},i.e.,  oldsymbol X oldsymbol{	heta} =  oldsymbol{y}.Note that the data points are the rows of the data matrix, i.e., every column is a dimension of the data. Our goal is to find the best $ oldsymbol	heta$ such that we minimize the following objective (least square).  egin{eqnarray} & \sum^n_{i=1}{\lVert  ar{y_i} - y_i Vert^2} \ &= \sum^n_{i=1}{\lVert  oldsymbol 	heta^T oldsymbol{x}_{i} - y_{i} Vert^2} \ &= ( oldsymbol X oldsymbol {	heta} -  oldsymbol y)^T( oldsymbol X oldsymbol {	heta} -  oldsymbol y). \end{eqnarray}If we set the gradient of the above objective to $ oldsymbol 0$, we have  egin{eqnarray} 
abla_	heta( oldsymbol X oldsymbol {	heta} -  oldsymbol y)^T( oldsymbol X oldsymbol {	heta} -  oldsymbol y) &=&  oldsymbol 0 \ 
abla_	heta( oldsymbol {	heta}^T oldsymbol X^T -  oldsymbol y^T)( oldsymbol X oldsymbol {	heta} -  oldsymbol y) &=&  oldsymbol 0 \ 
abla_	heta( oldsymbol {	heta}^T oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol X oldsymbol {	heta} -  oldsymbol y^T oldsymbol X oldsymbol 	heta -  oldsymbol 	heta^T oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol y +  oldsymbol y^T oldsymbol y ) &=&  oldsymbol 0 \ 2 oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol X	heta - 2 oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol y &=&  oldsymbol 0 \  oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol X oldsymbol 	heta &=&  oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol y. \end{eqnarray}The solution that gives zero gradient solves (which we call the maximum likelihood estimator) the following equation:  oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol X oldsymbol 	heta =  oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol y._This is exactly the same as the normal equation we have for projections_. This means that if we solve for $ oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol X oldsymbol 	heta =  oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol y.$ we would find the best $ oldsymbol 	heta = ( oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol X)^{-1} oldsymbol X^T oldsymbol y$, i.e. the $ oldsymbol 	heta$ which minimizes our objective. Letâ€™s put things into perspective. Consider that we want to predict the true coefficient $ oldsymbol 	heta$of the line $ oldsymbol y =  oldsymbol 	heta^T  oldsymbol x$ given only $ oldsymbol X$ and $ oldsymbol y$. We do not know the true value of $ oldsymbol 	heta$. Note: In this particular example, $ oldsymbol 	heta$ is a number. Still, we can represent it as an $\mathbb{R}^1$ vector. 12345678910x = np.linspace(0, 10, num=50)theta = 2def f(x): random = np.random.RandomState(42) # we use the same random seed so we get deterministic output return theta * x + random.normal(scale=1.0, size=len(x)) # our observations are corrupted by some noise, so that we do not get (x,y) on a liney = f(x)plt.scatter(x, y);plt.xlabel('x');plt.ylabel('y'); 12345X = x.reshape(-1,1) # size N x 1Y = y.reshape(-1,1) # size N x 1# maximum likelihood estimatortheta_hat = np.linalg.solve(X.T @ X, X.T @ Y) We can show how our $\hat{ oldsymbol 	heta}$ fits the line. 12345678fig, ax = plt.subplots()ax.scatter(x, y);xx = [0, 10]yy = [0, 10 * theta_hat[0,0]]ax.plot(xx, yy, 'red', alpha=.5)